      "rationale": "All nonlinear load steps converged to force residual norm < 1e-5 and energy criterion < 1e-6. No divergence or line-search failures were recorded across the 11 construct simulations. Solver error contribution is negligible relative to other uncertainty sources."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation inputs and boundary conditions must be independently reviewed by a second qualified analyst prior to execution.",
      "rationale": "All FEA setups (geometry, material assignments, contact definitions, boundary conditions, load application) were reviewed by a second analyst not involved in model construction. Review checklist completed with no discrepancies identified. Use error risk rated low."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The constitutive model and contact formulation must be justified by published literature for titanium alloy surgical implants under quasi-static bending; sensitivity analysis on model form assumptions required.",
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening (Ti-6Al-4V, E=114 GPa, σy=880 MPa, Et=2.5 GPa) was selected based on published tensile data and prior FDA FEA submissions. Augmented Lagrange contact with friction coefficient μ=0.2 is consistent with published pedicle screw tribology data. A model-form sensitivity study replacing bilinear hardening with Ramberg-Osgood showed <3% QoI shift, confirming robustness of the chosen form."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties must be sourced from lot-specific coupon testing or certified material certificates traceable to the implant lot; geometric inputs must derive from CMM measurements of tested specimens.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V material properties were obtained from tensile coupon tests on the same bar stock used for the N=11 test constructs (mean E=113.8 GPa, σy=876 MPa, CV<2%). Screw geometry was digitized via CMM at 0.005 mm resolution. UHMWPE block geometry was measured per ASTM F1717 fixture specifications. Input uncertainty quantified via Monte Carlo (1000 samples); 95th-percentile QoI spread <4%."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test constructs must be production-representative implants assembled per surgical technique; N≥10 specimens across at least two independent lots.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were assembled from two production lots (Lot A: n=6, Lot B: n=5) using the validated surgical technique guide. Constructs were inspected by QC prior to testing. Sample representativeness confirmed; between-lot variability in stiffness was 3.1%, within expected manufacturing tolerance."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must replicate ASTM F1717 requirements and include at least two loading rates or environmental conditions to bound in-vivo variability.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted per ASTM F1717 at a single displacement rate of 5 mm/min at ambient temperature (23°C). A second loading rate (1 mm/min) or physiological temperature (37°C) condition was not evaluated. Achieved level is Gradation 2; required level is Gradation 3. This gap is acknowledged as a limitation of the validation dataset. The shortfall is documented and accepted given that ASTM F1717 does not mandate rate variation and prior literature shows <5% rate sensitivity for Ti-6Al-4V constructs in this displacement range."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA input parameters (geometry, material, boundary conditions) must be demonstrably matched to the physical test configuration with documented traceability.",
      "rationale": "A parameter-equivalency matrix was completed mapping each FEA input to its experimental counterpart with measurement traceability. Screw geometry (CMM), material properties (coupon tests), fixture geometry (ASTM F1717 drawings), and loading configuration (crosshead displacement) are all directly matched. No surrogate or assumed inputs were used. Equivalency rated as fully achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval must be <1.96 for all three primary QoIs; graphical force-displacement overlay must be provided.",
      "rationale": "E/uval values: stiffness 0.81, yield force 1.34, force at 40 mm 1.71 — all below the 1.96 threshold. Force-displacement overlays for all 11 constructs are provided in Appendix B. The comparison framework follows ASME V&V 10.1 guidance. Output comparison criterion is fully met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) must be directly linked to the regulatory submission acceptance criteria and the clinical failure modes of interest.",
      "rationale": "Stiffness governs load transfer to adjacent vertebrae; yield force is the primary fatigue-initiation predictor; force at 40 mm corresponds to the ASTM F1717 endpoint for structural integrity assessment. All three QoIs appear explicitly in the 510(k) predicate device comparison and are accepted by FDA as relevant endpoints for pedicle screw submissions. QoI relevance is fully established."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must be shown to span the conditions of the COU including geometry envelope, load magnitude range, and material lot variability.",
      "rationale": "The assessment team determined that relevance of validation activities to the COU does not apply in a meaningful way to this specific submission context, as the validation and the COU are effectively co-located — the same bench test program constitutes both the validation evidence and the regulatory use case. Because the validation activity and the intended use are considered identical in scope, no separate relevance mapping was deemed necessary, and this factor was not formally scored. The team notes that this position is consistent with the view that relevance assessment is only required when the validation domain differs from the deployment domain."
    }
